{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a96488af-4a1a-4754-84c1-7257cadf58c9","content":"Here's my assessment of the template:\n\n**Not ready to publish.** Several issues:\n\n1. **No template content** — The directory only contains `.template.config/`. There are no source files (`.csproj`, `Program.cs`, etc.) for the template to scaffold.\n\n2. **Missing `$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for validation and editor support.\n\n3. **`Framework` symbol is inert** — It defines a `choice` parameter but has no `replaces` property, so the selected value is never substituted into generated files (e.g., `<TargetFramework>` in a `.csproj`).\n\n4. **No `.nuspec` or pack configuration** — You'll need a `.csproj` with `<PackageType>Template</PackageType>` (or a `.nuspec`) to actually produce a NuGet package.\n\n**To fix**, you'd need at minimum:\n- Actual project files (`MyWebApi.csproj`, `Program.cs`, etc.) alongside `.template.config/`\n- Add `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"` (or use a generated symbol) to the `Framework` symbol\n- A packaging project to produce the `.nupkg`","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"98b9388c-1e41-4bf1-8e51-4d7ff5bf1c59","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine schema requirements.\n\nIssues I can see:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not required but recommended for validation/IntelliSense.\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for template packs with multiple related templates.\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Not critical if there's only one template.\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Minor, defaults to false.\n5. **The `Framework` symbol replaces `sourceName`?** — No, the `Framework` symbol is defined but there's no `replaces` for it, so it won't actually do anything useful in the generated project. The symbol needs a `replaces` property to substitute the framework value into project files (like the `<TargetFramework>` element).\n\n\n6. **Core required fields are present** — `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author`, `sourceName`, `classifications`, and `tags` are all there, which covers the essentials for NuGet publishing. The main blocker is that the `Framework` parameter won't actually substitute into any files without a `replaces` property pointing to something like `net9.0`.\n\n7. **The template is missing actual project content** — There's no .csproj file, no Program.cs, no source files at all. The directory only contains `.template.config/`, which means this template would generate an empty project. That's the critical issue here.","outputTokens":804},"id":"d9bfbdba-d727-416d-8954-20bdbf44a9d6","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:37:15.918Z","parentId":"db59c473-f64a-4d64-981c-cbfe4ea37f8f"}
